                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase;">Cybersecurity</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">Pick n Pay says its old delivery app was breached</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2022/11/picknpay1-scaled.jpg" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                         <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: Reuters</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/03/03/techcabal-daily-tymes-up-for-pick-n-pay/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">Pick n Pay</a>, one of South Africa&rsquo;s biggest retailers, has just learned an awkward lesson about how the Internet&rsquo;s memory works: old apps never really die if you keep their data plugged in.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">The company has disclosed that a <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/06/01/pick-n-pay-cyberbreach/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">cyberattack exposed customer data</a> linked to an older version of its on-demand delivery service, first launched as &ldquo;Bottles&rdquo; and later rebranded as Asap!. The platform had long since been replaced, but the customer records apparently never got the memo.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>What did hackers access? </strong>The compromised data includes names, contact details, delivery addresses, and limited payment card information belonging to customers who signed up on or before 2022. Pick n Pay says full card numbers and card verification value (CVV) codes were not stored on the affected system, reducing the risk of direct card fraud.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Yet, the most interesting detail is not what was stolen. It is where it was sitting.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>The breach did not originate from Pick n Pay&#8217;s current digital infrastructure.</strong> Instead, it came from a retired platform that continued holding customer information years after it disappeared from public view. It points to a problem that extends far beyond one retailer: companies are getting better at launching digital products than shutting them down.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Every new app creates a database. Every database creates risk. And when old systems linger online, they can become soft targets for attackers long after the business has moved on.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Zoom out: </strong>South Africa&#8217;s tech sector has recently become a target for hackers. Following the high-profile March breach at Standard Bank, the country&#8217;s largest bank, which <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/04/17/%F0%9F%91%A8%F0%9F%8F%BF%F0%9F%9A%80techcabal-daily-a-standard-hack/#Story2" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">exposed customer names</a> and card details&mdash;specifically card numbers and expiry dates&mdash;as of the bank&#8217;s last update on April 14. Cyber attackers also <a href="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/security/649464-nigerian-hacking-group-claims-it-breached-sars.html" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">claimed</a> to have targeted government agencies, including the South African Revenue Service (SARS), the country&#8217;s taxman. The agency <a href="https://businesstech.co.za/news/finance/861458/sars-responds-to-data-breach-claims/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">denied</a> those claims.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">While in Pick n Pay&#8217;s case, the breach may have exposed data tied to a platform retired years ago, there is no telling how valuable it can become in the hands of data tracers and brokers who&#8217;d buy those IDs from them.</p>
</div>
